21 drawing impacted party.
22 (14) Alternative resolution of an investigation.
23 (a) At any time prior to the delivery of a final investigative report under subsection
24 (13)(g) or (i) of this rule, the Legislative Equity Officer may engage any impacted party and
25 the respondent in discussion about a voluntary alternative resolution of the investigation.
26 The officer may use:
27 (A) A formal mediation process;
28 (B) Informal negotiating between parties;
29 (C) Techniques of restorative justice to enable impacted parties and respondents to mu-
30 tually engage in repairing harms and establishing positive paths forward; or
31 (D) Any other voluntary means to resolve the investigation.
32 (b) Undertaking an alternative resolution of an investigation under this subsection sus-
33 pends the timeline for completion of an investigation under subsection (13) of this rule until
34 the Legislative Equity Officer concludes that alternative resolution of the investigation will
35 not be achieved. The officer shall inform the investigator of both the timeline suspension and
36 of the need to resume the investigation.
37 (c) An agreement or agreed-upon outcome under this subsection brings to conclusion any
38 investigation under subsection (13) of this rule with respect to:
39 (A) Any impacted party who joins in the alternative resolution efforts, but does not affect
40 any participating impacted party who did not join in the alternative resolution efforts; and
41 (B) The respondent only if every participating impacted party has agreed to the alterna-
42 tive resolution.
43 (d) The parties who voluntarily join efforts to achieve an alternative resolution to the
44 investigation do not waive any rights they may otherwise have under state or federal law.
45 (15) Remedial measures.
[18]

SCR 208
1 (a) In a case where the respondent is a member of the Legislative Assembly and the appropriate
2 committee on conduct has made a determination under subsection [(14)(g)] (13)(g) of this rule that
3 a violation of this rule has occurred, the committee shall impose any remedial measure that is suf-
4 ficient to reprimand the member and deter future conduct that violates the rule, including but not
5 limited to a reprimand, monetary fine or other remedy that the committee determines is appropriate
6 under the circumstances:
7 (A) Except that, if the committee recommendation is to expel the member, the committee shall
8 report that recommendation to the full chamber, which shall act on that recommendation at its
9 earliest opportunity;
10 (B) Except that, if the committee recommendation is to remove the member from one or more
11 committees to which the member is assigned, unless subparagraph (C) of this paragraph applies, the
12 committee shall report that recommendation to the presiding officer of that chamber; and
13 (C) Including the removal of the member from the committee on conduct. If a member is removed
14 from the committee on conduct under this subsection, the member also is removed from the Joint
15 Committee on Conduct.
16 (b)(A) In a case where the respondent is a Legislative Branch employee [in a nonpartisan staff
17 position], the appointing authority, in consultation with the Human Resources Director, shall deter-
18 mine an appropriate remedy that is consistent with the investigator’s determination that the re-
19 spondent violated the requirements of this rule.
